#### Li-6: Finding Restaurants
*Strategy:* Research + Decide
*See also:* Li-5: Planning Trips (for restaurants while traveling), Ch-5: Cooking and Culinary Skills (for eating in)
*My Man Jeeves:* _It would appear that the prevailing restaurant recommendation algorithms optimize for establishments that pay for placement or generate engagement, rather than for the most suitable meal in one's vicinity at one's price point for one's actual preferences. Your Agent maintains no paid placements. It will also, one feels compelled to note, refrain from passing judgment should one desire chicken fingers at an establishment with tablecloths._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I'm looking for a restaurant in [location] for [occasion:
date night / family dinner / quick lunch / celebration / solo meal].
Number of people: [X]
Budget: [per person range]
Must accommodate: [dietary restrictions, kids, wheelchair access,
noise sensitivity, etc.]
What I'm in the mood for: [cuisine type, or "surprise me"]
What I want to avoid: [specific dislikes or past bad experiences]
Give me 3-5 options with why each one fits, and tell me
which one you'd pick if you were me.
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Pick the one that fits your mood, not the one that sounds most impressive. Check the hours and whether you need a reservation — your Agent may not have current information. If you're going with other people, send them the short list and let them weigh in. The best restaurant for the night is the one everyone agrees to go to.

::: also
Checking current information requires web search, which is free in Gemini, ChatGPT, and Copilot. In Claude, web search requires the paid tier. See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


::: tip
_"I eat at [restaurant] once a week and I'm bored. Based on what I like about it — [describe] — what else should I try?"_
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The social anxiety of restaurant choice is underappreciated. Choosing "wrong" in front of others is a real fear — tied to social performance and class signaling. Picky eating in adults is increasingly understood as ARFID (Avoidant/Restrictive Food Intake Disorder) rather than a character flaw. Thomas et al. (2017) in International Journal of Eating Disorders is the key reference. The Skill should destigmatize food preferences while still encouraging exploration. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Tipping. The American tipping system is a post-Civil War practice that transferred the cost of wages from employers to customers, with documented racial origins. Jayaraman (2016) "Forked: A New Standard for American Dining" is the primary source. The tipped minimum wage ($2.13/hour federally) has not changed since 1991. Your Agent can explain current norms, but the system itself deserves a brief structural note. Connects to W-5 (Unions) and broader labor themes. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Solo dining stigma. Eating alone in public is culturally coded as failure in America but normalized elsewhere. The Skill could include a brief note destigmatizing it — your Agent can recommend restaurants with good bar seating or counter service for solo diners. Small thing, big psychological barrier. -->

