#### Li-8: Wellness Coach
*Strategy:* Research + Draft (Expert Role)
*See also:* H-8: Wellness and Nutrition Coach (for physical health), H-13: Understanding Addiction, H-1: Understanding a Diagnosis. Russ Harris, [_The Happiness Trap_](https://www.amazon.com/Happiness-Trap-Stop-Struggling-Start/dp/1590305841) (the ACT framework this Skill's thought-pattern work builds on)
*My Man Jeeves:* _A difficulty of some consequence presents itself in the matter of mental health care in America, where the median wait for a new patient appointment is, by research estimates, between six and ten weeks[^li8-1] and a single therapy session costs $100 to $250 out of pocket. One cannot help but observe that the persons who require assistance most urgently — the isolated, the overwhelmed, the financially strained — face the most formidable barriers to obtaining it. Your Agent is not a therapist. It is, however, available at 2 AM when the therapist is not, and it is capable of performing several things a therapist would recommend one do between sessions._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
Act as a supportive wellness coach. I am not in crisis —
I want to work on [specific goal: managing stress, building
a journaling habit, improving sleep, processing a difficult
period, developing coping strategies, understanding my patterns].
My situation: [relevant context]
What I've tried: [if anything]
What's getting in the way: [be honest — time, motivation,
shame, not knowing where to start]
Please:
1. Help me understand what might be going on
2. Suggest one specific practice I can start today
3. Tell me when this is something I should bring to
   a professional instead
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Start with the one thing. Not three things. One. If the Agent suggests journaling, write for five minutes tonight. If it suggests a breathing exercise, do it once. The compound effect of small consistent actions is better documented than the effect of ambitious plans that last three days.

::: fairness
Your Agent will recommend therapy when appropriate. If cost or access is the barrier, say so: _"I can't afford therapy right now. What can I do on my own that has the most evidence behind it?"_ The answer exists and is better than nothing.
:::


*Common wellness Expert Role specs:*
::: prompt
Act as a cognitive behavioral coach. I keep having this thought
pattern: [describe the loop — catastrophizing, rumination,
all-or-nothing thinking, etc.].
Help me identify what's happening and give me a specific
technique to interrupt it.
:::
::: prompt
Act as a journaling coach. I want to start journaling but
I don't know what to write about and I feel self-conscious.
Give me a simple framework I can use for 5-10 minutes a day
that doesn't require me to be a good writer.
:::
::: prompt
Act as an occupational therapy coach. I am struggling with
[daily living task: morning routine, household organization,
time management, sensory overload, task initiation] and I want
practical strategies, not motivational advice.
:::

[^li8-1]: Busch, S.H. et al. (2022). "Wait Times for New Psychiatric Appointments." _Psychiatric Services_, 73(12). In-person psychiatry median 67 days; telepsychiatry 43 days.

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Therapy wait time data. NAMI and APA have surveys but the 48-day figure needs verification — some sources say 25 days median, others longer. Rural areas are much worse. The structural access problem is well-documented regardless of the exact figure. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The stigma of seeking help is declining in surveys but persists in behavior. Men are half as likely as women to seek mental health treatment (SAMHSA NSDUH data). The Skill should destigmatize without lecturing — the reader who needs this Skill most is the one least likely to have read this far. The Agent as a "safe first step" is a genuine use case, not a consolation prize. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Journaling has surprisingly strong evidence. Pennebaker's expressive writing paradigm (1986, replicated extensively) shows measurable immune function improvement from writing about difficult experiences for 15-20 minutes over 3-4 days. The mechanism is not fully understood — possibly narrative coherence, possibly emotional processing, possibly both. Pennebaker & Beall (1986) in Journal of Abnormal Psychology is the foundational citation. This is one of the cheapest, most accessible, most evidence-backed interventions in psychology and it is culturally coded as either feminine or pretentious, which suppresses adoption. Deserves its own science callout. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The intention-action gap — the gap between knowing what to do and doing it — is the central problem in wellness. Sheeran & Webb (2016) meta-analysis found that even large changes in intention produce only small-to-medium changes in behavior. The problem is not information. The problem is that humans are not rational actors responding to information. We are pattern-running organisms embedded in environments that cue our existing patterns. Changing behavior requires changing cues, not just knowledge. This is the honest truth your Agent cannot fix, but it can help you design cue changes. This insight connects to every Skill in the book but belongs here. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: When to escalate to professional help. The Skill needs a clear, non-alarming framework for "this is beyond what self-help can do." PHQ-9 and GAD-7 are standard screening tools — your Agent can walk you through them as a self-assessment, not a diagnosis. Crisis resources should be in the Skill, not buried in a footnote: 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline, Crisis Text Line (text HOME to 741741). -->

